About
Visit Craven Cottage, the iconic home of Fulham Football Club, London's oldest professional football club. Walk in the footsteps of some of the greatest players to ever play the game; marvel at the 1905 Pavilion, designed by the legendary Archibald Leitch and try a seat in the Johnny Haynes Stand, named after the clubs greatest player and England captain, the first £100 a week player. Take a seat in the changing room, imagine you are playing in the match and listening to the Head Coach give a team talk. Take your place in the dugout and players tunnel and walk in the footsteps of George Cohen, the only English right-back to win the World Cup, back in 1966. The ground is traditional, historical and fascinating. Our tours are all led by an official guide who will be delighted to show you a truly special, famous and iconic ground. We cannot wait to show you around. Come on Fulham!
Duration: 1-2 hours

  • Haydon R
    Norwich, United Kingdom4 contributions
    A visit to the home of football.
    After a short walk through Bishop's Park we arrived at Craven Cottage right alongside the wonderful statue of Johnny Haynes, where the tour started once we had signed in at the reception. We were introduced to our Tour Guides, Will and Joey, who led us into the ground to start the tour. We were privileged to be there on October 10th as it was 127 years to the day that Fulham played their first match on this ground. (We were all given a small memento of the occasion). First we were given a demonstration of how small the turnstiles are as this part of the ground is a Grade 1 Listed Building and no alterations can be made. From there we were guided through the Johnny Haynes Stand with it's wooden seats well over 100 years old. As a lifelong Fulham supporter my dream was always one day to go inside the "Cottage" well today we did. We ascended the steps into the lounge and then out onto the balcony of the Cottage. To see the ground from there was breathtaking, a dream come true. Thinking about all the countless footballers and celebrities who have stood there over the past 100 or more years was just amazing. We then visited the dressing rooms where in the "home" dressing room the shirts of the current first team squad are hanging on hooks ready for the next game. We saw the physio room and the small gym. The "away" dressing room was not quite so plush, but then why would it be? We then walked through the tunnel onto the pitch area, although we obviously were not allowed to walk on the hallowed turf. Then it was over to the new stand, which is reputed to be costing Fulham Chairman, Shahid Khan, £120m and season tickets will be £3,000 a time which is the highest in the Football League. However, if you want to watch the "best" you have to pay for it. Then it was back through the "Hammy" end to the Trophy Room. Not many trophies in there but who needs trophies when the enjoyment is in watching Fulham. Then it was through the club shop and the tour was over. Will gave us a wonderful guided tour telling us many bits of information about players and matches over the years and all aspects of the ground itself. The whole tour was at our pace, (I am in my 80s and I have difficulties walking) and we were encouraged to ask as many questions and take as many photos we wanted. The tour took well over an hour. It was a wonderful experience and we were all made to feel special. It is well worth a visit even if you aren't a Fulham supporter. Thank you Fulham FC for the wonderful time we all had.
    Visited October 2023
